{{Infobox musical artist | honorific_prefix = | birth_name = Malam Mamane Barka | honorific_suffix = | image = Malam Maman Barka.jpg | image_upright = | image_size = 300px | landscape = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank --> | alt = | caption = | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | birth_date = 1958/1959 | birth_place = [[Tesker, Niger]] | origin = | death_date = {{Death date and given age|2018|11|21|59|df=y}} | death_place = [[Niamey|Niamey, Niger]] | instrument = Biram, Ngurumi | years_active = <!-- YYYY–YYYY (or –present) --> | label = [[World Music Network]] | occupation = Musician }}
'''Malam Mamane Barka''' (1958/1959 – 21 November 2018) was a [[Niger]]ien musician, and one of the world's most prominent players of the ''biram''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sole|first1=Deanne|title=Mamane Barka: Introducing Mamane Barka|url=https://www.popmatters.com/93025-mamane-barka-introducing-mamane-barka-2496019943.html|website=Pop Matters|accessdate=4 February 2018|date=18 May 2009}}</ref> He died on 21 November 2018, aged 59.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.aniamey.com/h/89128.html|title=Décès du musicien Mamane Mallam Barka ce mercredi à Niamey|website=aniamey.com|language=French|access-date=26 November 2018}}</ref>
==Biography== Malam Mamane Barka was born in 1958 or 1959 in [[Tesker, Niger|Tesker, a town in the east of the then autonomous republic of Niger]]. He came from the nomadic people of Toubou. As a player of the Ngurumi, a two-string plucked instrument, he gained popularity in his homeland and neighboring Nigeria. In 2002 he decided to devote himself to the study of Biram. It is a five-stringed instrument used by the Boudouma, a fishing community on Lake Chad, for traditional songs.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
