{{Infobox artist | honorific_prefix = | name = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name --> | honorific_suffix = | image = Rhoda Astley (née Delaval) by Arthur Pond.jpg<!-- just the pagename, without the File:/Image: prefix or [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = [[Arthur Pond]]'s portrait of Rhoda Delaval | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = Rhoda Delaval<!--only use if different from name--> | birth_date = 1 July 1725<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead --> | birth_place = [[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom]] | death_date = 1757<!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = London, England, United Kingdom | resting_place = [[Widcombe, Bath]], England, United Kingdom | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = British | education = via Arthur Pond | alma_mater = | known_for = Portraiture | notable_works = | style = | movement = | spouse = [[Sir Edward Astley, 4th Baronet|Edward Astley]] (1751-) | awards = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) --> | elected = | patrons = | memorials = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | module = }} [[Image:Seaton Delaval Hall - all from NW with tree.jpg|thumb|right|[[Seaton Delaval Hall]], built by the Delavals and the former seat of the Astley family]] '''Rhoda Delaval Astley''' (1 July 1725 – 1757) was an English aristocrat and artist. She was married to [[Sir Edward Astley, 4th Baronet|Edward Astley]], with whom she had a daughter and three sons. Lady Astley studied painting with [[Arthur Pond]], who painted her portrait. [[Seaton Delaval Hall]] passed from the Delaval family to the Astley family through her descendants.
==Early life== Rhoda Delaval was born on 1 July 1725 to Captain [[Francis Blake Delaval (1692–1752)|Francis Blake Delaval]] (the elder) and Rhoda Apreece and baptized at [[St George's, Hanover Square]] in London{{r|National Trust}}{{r|Northumberland}} on 22 July 1725.{{r|Cole}}{{rp|133}} She was their oldest daughter{{r|National Trust}} of 12 children.{{r|Jeffares}} Her siblings were Anne Hussey, Mary Elizabeth, Sarah, Robert, George, Henry, Ralph, Francis, Edward, Thomas, [[John Delaval, 1st Baron Delaval|John]].{{r|Northumberland}} Two years after her birth, her brother, [[Francis Blake Delaval (1727–1771)|Sir Francis Blake Delaval]] (the younger) (1727–1771) was born.{{r|BBC 1}} A brother George, who died as a young adult, also pursued the art of painting with her instructor, [[Arthur Pond]]. She was known to be a talented, beautiful woman.{{r|Jeffares}} One of her sisters was [[John Savile, 1st Earl of Mexborough|Sarah, Countess of Mexborough]].{{r|Jeffares}}
==Marriage and children== [[File:11 Downing Street - geograph.org.uk - 253377.jpg|thumb|[[11 Downing Street]] (grey building), London]] On 23 May 1751,{{r|Northumberland}} she married [[Sir Edward Astley, 4th Baronet|Edward Astley]], who became the 4th Baronet of [[Melton Constable]].{{r|National Trust}} They lived at [[11 Downing Street]] when in London.{{r|Jeffares}} Astley gave birth to four children, one daughter and three sons.{{r|National Trust}} Editha Rhoda was born 14 April 1755 and died by 12 May, when she was brought to be buried. Edward was born and died by 1757 and Francis was born in 1757.{{r|Cole}}{{rp|133–134}}{{r|Holt}} [[Sir Jacob Astley, 5th Baronet|Jacob Henry]] was born 12 September 1756.{{r|National Trust}}{{r|Cole}}{{rp|134}}
She died in 1757 following the birth of Francis{{r|National Trust}}{{r|Cole}}{{rp|133–134}} and was buried 21 October 1757 at [[Widcombe, Bath]]{{r|Northumberland}} with her son Edward and daughter Edith Rhoda at a church near the manor.{{r|Cole}}{{rp|133–134}}
Edward Astley lived at [[Melton Constable]] with his children after her death.{{r|National Trust}} Her letters, before and after her marriage, describe the personal daily lives of the people she knew in Northumberland.{{r|National Trust}} As the result of Edward and Rhoda's marriage, [[Seaton Delaval Hall]] came into the Astley family in 1814 through Jacob, when none of her brothers produced a male heir.{{r|National Trust}}{{r|Cole}}{{rp|134}}
==Artist== Periodically between 1744 and 1750, Astley studied art under Arthur Pond, who also painted her portrait.{{r|National Trust}}{{r|Jeffares}} She purchased prints for about £1,500 ({{inflation|UK|1,500|1750|cursign=£|fmt=eq}}) from Pond.{{r|Jeffares}}
The [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]] has the painting of her drawing with pastels.{{r|National Trust}} Her painting of [[Jacob Astley, 1st Baron Astley of Reading|Sir Jacob Astley]], 1st Baron Astley of Reading was made from a 17th-century original painting.{{r|BBC 2}} She made a painting of herself and her brother entitled ''Painting and Poetry'', patterned after [[Bernardino Luini]].{{r|BBC 1}} The painting of Anne Hussey Delaval (1737–1812), Lady Stanhope in the National Trust is attributed to Rhoda Delaval and is loan by Lord Hastings.{{r|BBC 3}} Lady Anne Delaval Stanhope was Astley's sister.{{r|Cole}}{{rp|183}} She had been commissioned, for a total of about £300 ({{inflation|UK|300|1750|cursign=£|fmt=eq}}), to paint portraits of her sisters and brothers.{{r|Jeffares}}
<gallery mode="packed" heights="200px" caption="[[Seaton Delaval]], [[Northumberland]], [[National Trust]]"> File:Rhoda Delaval, Sir Jacob Astley, 1st Baron Astley of Reading, Seaton Delaval, Northumberland, National Trust.jpg|[[Jacob Astley, 1st Baron Astley of Reading|Sir Jacob Astley]] (1579–1651/1652), 1st Baron Astley of Reading File:Rhoda Delaval (1725–1757), Later Lady Astley, and Her Brother, Sir Francis Blake Delaval (1727–1771), as 'Painting and Poetry' (after Bernardino Luini), Seaton Delaval, National Trust.jpg|Rhoda Delaval (1725–1757), Later Lady Astley, and Her Brother, [[Francis Blake Delaval (1727–1771)|Sir Francis Blake Delaval]] (1727–1771) File:Rhoda Delaval, Anne Hussey Delaval (1737–1812), Lady Stanhope , Seaton Delaval, Northumberland, National Trust.jpg|Anne Hussey Delaval (1737–1812), Lady Stanhope </gallery>
[[James MacArdell]] made an engraving of her self-portrait.{{r|Jeffares}} In 1756, her portrait was painted by [[Joshua Reynolds]]{{r|Jeffares}} and the painting was at [[Ford Castle]] in 1897. Another painting of her is in [[Doddington Hall, Lincolnshire]].{{r|Cole}}{{rp|133}}
